{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"5e2a3890-c49d-47d1-b5f0-cc118e039e00","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the `cpu-sampling` profile. Here's the workflow:\n\n**1. Install the tool inside the pod:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod> -- bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\nexport PATH=\"$PATH:$HOME/.dotnet/tools\"\n```\n\n**2. Find your process ID:**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n**3. Collect the trace (30s example):**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:00:30\n```\n\n**4. Copy the `.nettrace` file out:**\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod>:/path/to/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**5. Analyze** by opening `trace.nettrace` in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or [Speedscope](https://www.speedscope.app) (convert first with `dotnet-trace convert --format speedscope`).\n\n**Tips:**\n- If you can't install tools (distroless image), use the **sidecar approach** or enable the [dotnet-monitor](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/core/diagnostics/dotnet-monitor) container as a sidecar.\n- For a quick look without collecting a file, `dotnet-counters monitor -p <PID>` shows live CPU/GC metrics.\n- Prefer `dotnet-trace` over `perf` — it understands managed frames out of the box.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c81c8587-5db6-426b-ac13-6a3c20552832","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a diagnostic/troubleshooting question, not a code change request. I'll provide a concise answer based on my knowledge.","outputTokens":447,"requestId":"7845:2BEA6E:1E91C6C:21EBD7F:69FA9909"},"id":"ed5e39db-2029-4720-9b2d-439166d88bbe","timestamp":"2026-05-06T01:27:50.119Z","parentId":"281cb78e-cb71-4cd2-b1d2-48545cc2a374"}
